TY  - JOUR
AU  - Qiu, JS
AU  - Niu, GH
AU  - Li, LL
AU  - Li, L
AU  - Hu, XL
AU  - Li, XT
TI  - Study on damage evolution law and pore structure deterioration of recycled composite micro-powder concrete under freeze-thaw action
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - In preparing recycled aggregate from construction waste, recycled concrete powder (Recycled Concrete Powder, RCP) and recycled brick powder (Recycled Brick Powder, RBP) are produced, which makes the utilisation rate of construction waste low. Mixing RCP and RBP according to the mass ratio of 2 8 to prepare recycled brick mixed powder (Recycled Brick Mixed Powder, RBMP) instead of cement to prepare recycled brick-concrete micro-powder concrete (Recycled BrickConcrete Micro-Powder Concrete, RB-CMP) can effectively increase the utilisation rate of construction waste, reduce the separation cost, and reduce the amount of cement, which has C economy and environmental protection. Therefore, this paper uses a 0.45 water-binder ratio, RBMP replaces cement with 0 %, 10 %, 20 % and 30 % replacement rates, and sets 0.35 and 0.55 water-binder ratios based on the 20 % dosage group to prepare RB-CMP. In this paper, with a 0.45 water-binder ratio, RBMP replaces cement with replacement rates of 0 %, 10 %, 20 %, and 30 %, and RB-CMP is prepared by setting 0.35 and 0.55 water-binder ratios based on the 20 % dosage group. The macroscopic damage and pore structure degradation of RB-CMP under freeze-thaw action were studied using macro and micro test methods. The results show that: (1) The maximum frost resistance times of RB-CMP with 0 %, 10 %, 20 %, and 30 % RBMP content was 140 times, 120 times, 100 times, and 80 times. When freeze-thawed 80 times, compared with undoped RBMP, the mass loss rate and damage layer thickness of RB-CMP with 10 %, 20 %, and 30 % RBMP content increased by 0.02 %, 0.09 %, 0.13 %, and 1.03 mm, 8.03 mm, and 11.96 mm, respectively. The relative elastic modulus and compressive strength decreased by 1.82 %, 14.4 %, 21.24 %, 4.3 MPa, 12.5 MPa, and 15.9 MPa, respectively. (2) The ultrasonic wave velocity ratio of the damaged layer and the undamaged layer is used to modify the damage degree defined by the thickness of the damaged layer, and the freeze-thaw damage evolution model is established with the modified damage variable of the thickness of the damaged layer. The model's reliability is more significant than 0.9, which can better predict the freeze-thaw damage of RB-CMP under freeze-thaw action. (3) With the increase in RBMP content, the adequate pore size of RB-CMP accounted for 64.09 %, 58.49 %, and 57.03 %, respectively. The fractal dimension was introduced to characterise the pore-deterioration characteristics of RB-CMP. The fractal dimension was linearly related to the macroscopic properties, and the correlation coefficients were all greater than 0.9. (4) The RB-CMP of RBMP with a water-cement ratio of 0.45 and 20 % is enough to complete the secondary hydration reaction. The remaining part of RBMP begins to act as a filling effect, and RBMP can refine some pores. The appropriate amount of RBMP incorporation can optimise the pore structure to a certain extent.
