TY  - JOUR
AU  - Naraian, R
AU  - Gedam, VV
AU  - Unnikrishnan, S
TI  - Integrating green building rating systems with circular economy - A critical analysis and future pathways
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - The focus of the study is to critically assess the circularity potential of globally recognised building rating systems. The preliminary investigation suggests that there is limited research on construction and demolition waste management (C&DWM) within the Green Building Rating System (GBRS), although the theme holds considerable significance in incorporating CE within the construction industry. To investigate the circularity of the existing parameters of three chosen GBRS, i.e., Building Research Establishment Environmental Assessment Method (BREEAM), Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) and Green Rating for Integrated Habitat Assessment (GRIHA), associated with C&DWM, a framework grounded in the European Union (EU) Waste Hierarchy Framework (WHF) has been proposed. The WHF is used to derive nine themes, i.e., impact assessment, use phase or other building material waste, design adaptability, Environmental Product Declarations (EDPs), sourcing commitment, durability assessment, efficiency, refurbishment and site efficiency, which have then been categorised for circularity stages. Furthermore, the assessment highlights the gaps in the respective GBRS and outlines the potential improvements to enhance their alignment with the CE. The significant contribution of the study is that it identified various themes that are completely missing from the GBRS parameters. While the theme of 'Aggregate productivity' is lacking in BREEAM and GRIHA, the 'Project management' theme is missing from LEED. Moreover, the assessment of the existing and proposed Indian C&DW Rules, 2016 and 2025, against the nine themes and WHF highlights that the 'Aggregate Productivity' and 'EDPs' themes are absent. Thus, the findings of the study indicate that there remains a future scope for improvement within the three GBRS and also for the Indian policy framework. The major significance of the study is that it can help policymakers and other stakeholders to bridge the gaps in the rating system.
