TI  - EXPERIMENTAL RESEARCH ON ROAD BASE MADE OF RECYCLED AGGREGATE FROM WASTE CONCRETE IN COMPLEX ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS
T2  - JOURNAL OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND ECOLOGY
AB  - The recycling and reuse of waste concrete not only curb environmental pollution, but also save natural aggregate resources, bringing remarkable social, economic and environmental benefits. This paper prepares recycled aggregate from waste concrete, and determines its basic properties: apparent density (AD), water absorption (WA), crushing index (CI), and bulk density (BD). On this basis, the authors theoretically analysed the feasibility of replacing natural aggregate with recycled aggregate to make road lime-fly ash concrete (LFAC), and experimentally determined the main performance indices of recycled aggregate lime-fly ash macadam, including peak dry density (PDD), optimal water content (OWC), unconfined compressive strength (UCS), and indirect tensile strength (ITS). The results demonstrate the feasibility of lime-fly ash stabilised aggregate base in road engineering.
