TI  - Impact of silica fume on the fire resistance of aerogel insulation mortars incorporating decoration waste in freeze-thaw environments
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - The rapid expansion of urbanization and demolition activities has sharply increased construction and demolition waste(CDW), with decoration waste (DW) being a major component. Although decoration waste aggregates (DWRA) have been explored for use in construction materials, there remain challenges in ensuring their durability, especially in cold regions subjected to freeze-thaw (F-T) cycles and high-temperature fire exposure. Specifically, the high water absorption and porous structure of DWRA present significant issues for material performance under extreme conditions, which have not been fully addressed in prior research. This study investigates silica fume (SF) as a modifier to enhance the F-T durability and fire resistance of aerogel-based insulation mortars incorporating DWRA. A series of tests, including material preparation, freeze-thaw cycling, fire exposure, and microstructural analysis, were conducted to evaluate the impact of different SF dosages (0 %, 3 %, 6 %, 9 %, 12 %, and 15 %) on the thermal and mechanical properties of the mortars. The results show that incorporating SF reduces the initial thermal conductivity, improves insulation performance, bond strength retention and resistance to mass loss under combined F-T and fire exposure, and limits the increase in thermal conductivity after damage. Among all mixtures, the mortar with about 9 % SF exhibits the most balanced behavior after 30 F-T cycles and subsequent fire exposure, with only a slight increase in thermal conductivity (about 10.3 %), a relatively high residual tensile bond strength (0.932 MPa) and a low mass loss (1.34 %). The incorporation of SF therefore improves the overall durability of decoration waste aerogel insulation mortars (DWAM) in cold regions. An SF dosage of about 9 % provides the best compromise among thermal, mechanical and mass-loss properties and can serve as a practical guideline for designing sustainable, high-performance external insulation systems for cold-region construction.
