AU  - Ji, J
AU  - Zheng, WH
AU  - Jin, SS
AU  - Liu, CX
AU  - Wen, L
AU  - Qiu, C
TI  - Preparation via composite modification, enhanced properties, and multi-technique microstructural mechanisms of recycled brick-concrete aggregates using response surface methodology
T2  - JOURNAL OF BUILDING ENGINEERING
AB  - The construction and demolition waste (CDW) sector is generating increasing quantities of recycled brick-concrete aggregates (RB-CAs), which hold potential as alternative aggregates for road construction following appropriate treatment. However, current modification techniques for RB-CAs often involve complex machinery and high energy consumption, rendering them economically unviable for large-scale application. In this study, a composite modification approach is proposed, integrating nano-silica (NS) infiltration, ultrahigh-strength cementitious (UHSC) coating, and water-glass treatment. This method aims to enhance the physical and mechanical properties of RB-CAs and to investigate the underlying reinforcement mechanisms. Specifically, the RB-CAs are reinforced, and the optimal preparation parameters are determined using response surface methodology (RSM). After optimization, the moisture absorption of the enhanced RB-CAs (E-RB-CAs) is reduced by 56 % (from 9.4 % to 4.1 %), and the crushing value is reduced by 71 % (from 47 % to 13.7 %). To investigate the pore size distribution and elemental composition of different types of aggregates, mercury intrusion porosimetry (MIP), X-ray diffraction (XRD), X-ray fluorescence spectrometry (XRF), scanning electron microscopy (SEM), and contact angle were used. Consequently, the strengthened RB-CAs exhibit smoother surfaces and reduced porosity. Moreover, there are no obvious defects in the interfacial transition zone (ITZ), and abundant hydration products, such as Ca(OH)2, exist in the ITZ. The reinforcement mechanism of E-RB-CAs at different stages was subsequently analyzed via 3D profilometry, electron probe X-ray microanalyzer (EPMA), and thermogravimetric analysis-differential scanning calorimetry (TG-DSC). Upon reinforcement treatment, dense hydration products are formed both on the surface and in the internal capillary pores of the composites, which leads to the gradual expansion of calcium aluminate hydrate and a wider distribution of S, ultimately resulting in an increase in the macroscopic strength. After reinforcement, the apparent morphology of the E-RB-CAs becomes more abundant. In addition, cost analysis and feasibility evaluation indicate the proposed treatment is economically viable and suitable for industrial application. Overall, these results contribute to the sustainable management and application of CDW in pavement engineering.
